caption: I celebrated my PhD today in this delicious restaurant. Well we passed a marvelous evening and the restaurant was no doubt one of the reasons for the strong celebration. I used to love this place. It was one of my favorite sushi spots and I would order take out there once a week. The last handful of times have completely turned me off, and I won’t be ordering from them anymore. The orders are consistently wrong now, with ingredients or whole items missing or instructions not followed, and the food I have gotten prepared properly just doesn’t taste as good as it used to. For example, I got a tuna avocado roll with no avocado. And I got a tom yum noodle soup with no noodles. It’s not like it’s a small thing I can overlook— it usually ruins my dinner. I’m so so disappointed and feel like I just had to break up with an old lover. Lol. Ah well, at least I still have Umi.

I have been coming to Tono Sushi for about 15 years.  But, after tonight, never again.  My wife is allergic to fish; so, whenever she is out of town,  I have headed to Tono Sushi for sushi, sashimi, and the rest.  In general, the food has been acceptable and the service has been attentive.  The happy-hour-$1 sushi were small, but what can one expect for $1 and the qualify was a solid B--not great, but not bad either.  A decent buy, at the price.  So, I kept coming back.  Not again.  Something bad has happened.  The service, once brisk, was inattentive and indifferent.  Sitting at the bar, I was left entirely alone for 15-20 minute stretches and got service only when I turned around and and stared at the wait staff.  Specials advertised on the board over the bar were not available.  The ginger with the sushi was dried out and rubbery.  The $1 sushi, once small but acceptable, were microscopic.  Sushi is available at other places at similar prices and superior quality.  I'll drive a bit farther to enjoy a meal next time.

Unfortunately, I have not had any luck with restaurants recently. Today, I have to say that Tono Sushi had become another addition to the list of disappointment.  My S.O. and I arrived on Sunday at around 3pm, asked to sit outside and was told by a server that we could not because a storm was coming. We stepped outside and called the restaurant to speak with the manager. The manager, Pete, totally contradicted what the server said. Pete said that we were more than welcome to sit outside if we wanted to. He explained that the server was worried that a storm was coming. I did not know that their servers also double up as meteorologists. Plus, since it was so quiet in the restaurant, we could very easily move into the restaurant as needed. We proceeded to sit outside, not a single raindrop fell in the entire duration that we were there.  We were happy to see that they offered $1 sushi on Sundays from 12-7:30pm. We ordered some nigiri from the $1 sushi list, as well as a rainbow roll and a soft shell crab roll. The $1 nigiris were about a quarter of a normally sized nigiri, with the sliced fish so thin that it barely stays on the rice. It looked like it was going to get blown away any minute. The fish did not taste fresh at all and rice fell apart when we tried to pick it up. When we got the other two rolls, immediately we thought they did not look right. They were sloppily cut and had an excess amount of rice and things that did not belong inside them. The rainbow sushi had way too much fried panko in it and the color of the fish looked dull. The soft shell crab roll tasted awful, simply due to the fact that the crab was old. The crab tasted very "fishy" and had a stink to it. We did not touch the rainbow roll and took two pieces from the soft shell crab roll. We told the server that we did not want the rainbow roll, we wanted to return it and we were not happy with the soft shell crab roll. The waiter did not apologize, merely said "oh ok", took the rainbow roll and left.  Finally, the manager, Pete, came out again with the rainbow roll that was brought back, demanding to know what was wrong with it. When we indicated to him that it was not fresh. He became extremely defensive, told us that the fish was fresh and that he knows sushi and how it is supposed to be. Instead of asking us how he could make our experience better, he was argumentative, abrupt and rude.  This was not the first time we had a bad experience at Tono Sushi, we thought we would try again. Now we know that we will not be returning ever again!

Considering that weather has changed for the better, my friends and I decided to take a stroll out at the zoo. Afterwards, we walked along Connecticut to find a place to grab something to eat. We have heard some great things about Tono Sushi so we decided to go there. When we arrived, it was after lunch hour. When we asked to sit outside, the server suggested that we should sit inside. It seemed like he did not want to go in/out of the restaurant and preferred to stay inside. When we spoke with the manager (Pete), manager told us that we were able to sit outside. So we did.  They offer a HH menu on Sundays, all nigiris are $1. We thought we would try some along with other dishes. I also got the tonkatsu ramen with charsiu.  When we got the nigiris, they looked like a huge joke. They were tiny bite-size pieces that were laughable, with barely any fish on them! When I asked the manager, Pete, about it, he said that is what is provided at HH price. Nowhere on the menu does it say that the sushi would shrink during HH. As if I went to an American restaurant and got a burger at HH price, I would get a slider instead?!  In addition, the ramen was way too salty. The noodles were overcooked and soggy. They charge $2-3 for anything extra! Even things that are supposed to come with ramen, such as bamboo shoots, nori and naurto.  The worst part is that no one even attempted service recovery. They brushed us off and gave us "this is what you get" kind of attitude... very discouraging! To me, management and leadership is very questionable at this restaurant.  This was a very disappointing experience. I am assuming it has gone down hill and is no longer like the old days. I do not plan on returning again

My biggest issue with this place is the level of service. You don't really seem to have a specific server so no one's tracking where you are in your meal. It started out good but I was done and it was a good 15 minutes before anyone came over. The faster you turn the tables the more customers you can get in the door. I lived in Asia for years so I'm familiar witg service styles there but that doesn't always work in the states. If you want me to get your attention when i need something, put a bell on the table. On the positive side, the happy hour is pretty good. The edamame was a little overdone because it was falling apart.
Good deal for lunch

I was not that impressed. I had the California Roll with cream cheese. The rice was very gummy and the "Real" had no taste. On a good note, the staff was excellent! The sake was very good. I hope I just caught them on a bad night. Other reviews are good.
